        Home Insurance During Your Sale Campaign: What Brisbane Sellers Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        From the moment you list to settlement day, your insurance obligations are more complex than most sellers realise. Here is what to check before your campaign starts.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers check their building insurance once a year at renewal and then forget about it. When you are selling, that approach is not good enough. The period from listing to settlement introduces specific insurance risks that a standard home policy may not fully cover, and Queensland's contract law means the seller carries risk for longer than many people expect. Getting this wrong can be expensive.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why insurance matters during the campaign</h2>
      <p>Once your property is listed and open homes begin, strangers are walking through your home on a regular basis. If a visitor is injured during an inspection or open home, a public liability claim can follow. Most standard home insurance policies include a public liability component, but the adequacy of that cover is worth confirming with your insurer before the campaign starts. The coverage limit, what is and is not included, and whether the policy conditions have been met are all worth reviewing.</p>

      <p>Beyond liability, the physical property itself remains at risk during a campaign. A break-in, a storm event, or accidental damage mid-campaign can delay or unwind a sale. A buyer who has exchanged contracts and discovers the property has been damaged before settlement has grounds to seek a price reduction or, in serious cases, to walk away. The seller who has maintained adequate insurance cover is in a far stronger position to deal with that situation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Queensland law: risk stays with the seller until settlement</h2>
      <p>This is the point that surprises many Brisbane sellers. In Queensland, the risk of damage to a property does not transfer to the buyer at exchange. It transfers at settlement. This is different from some other Australian states, where risk passes to the buyer on exchange.</p>

      <p>What this means in practice: if your property is damaged after contracts are exchanged but before settlement, the responsibility for that damage sits with you as the seller. If the damage is significant, you are generally required to repair it or offer the buyer a price reduction. Without adequate insurance, you may be funding those repairs out of pocket while the sale is still live. Maintaining your building insurance right through to settlement day is not optional.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the property is vacant</h2>
      <p>Sellers who have already moved out before their property sells need to pay particular attention to their policy terms. Most standard home insurance policies contain a vacancy clause that limits or excludes cover after the property has been unoccupied for a continuous period, commonly 60 to 90 days depending on the insurer. If your property sits on the market for longer than your insurer's vacancy threshold, you may find yourself without meaningful cover precisely when you need it most.</p>

      <p>If you have moved out and the property is vacant, contact your insurer before your campaign starts. Some insurers offer a specific vacant property endorsement or a short-term vacant property policy. Others will simply adjust the terms of your existing policy for the campaign period. Either way, do not assume your standard policy covers an empty home on the same terms it covers an occupied one.</p>

      <p>Contents insurance under a vacant property is also worth reviewing. Standard contents policies typically offer reduced or no cover once a property is unoccupied. If you have left furniture or valuables in the property to assist with presentation, check the policy terms carefully and remove any items that fall outside cover.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers are responsible for</h2>
      <p>A buyer may choose to take out their own insurance on the property from the date of exchange. Some buyers do this as a precaution, particularly for high-value purchases. However, the buyer's decision to insure does not reduce your obligation to maintain your own cover. The seller must carry insurance through to settlement regardless of what the buyer has arranged on their side.</p>

      <p>It is worth being clear with your conveyancer about the settlement date and ensuring your insurance policy does not lapse before that date. If you pay insurance annually and your policy renewal falls during the campaign or settlement period, renew it. The cost of a renewal is trivial compared to the cost of an uninsured damage event in the final weeks of a sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical checklist before you list</h2>
      <p>Before your campaign launches, work through these four steps. First, confirm your building insurance is current and the coverage amount reflects the rebuild cost of the property, not just the purchase price. Second, check your policy's public liability limit and whether open homes are covered under standard terms. Third, if the property will be vacant during the campaign, notify your insurer and ask specifically about vacancy conditions. Fourth, confirm your policy will remain active through to your anticipated settlement date and note any renewal dates that fall within that window.</p>

      <p>None of this takes long. Your insurer can answer most of these questions in a single phone call. The sellers who run into problems are almost always those who assume their existing policy is fine without checking.</p>

